Predominantly dyke-pegmatite as for 151.45.  Common py +/- cpy in veins and blebs.

Fine-grained plag-pyrox-(qtz-mag) rock.  Some coarse grained recrystallised magnetite. Cut by hem/kspar altered, medium- to coarse-grained qtz-feld dykes 1-10cm thick.  Foliation and banding more obious from 168.3m.
Cross cutting zone of carbonate-qtz-hem-pyx alteration.

Qtz-feld-pyx coarse grained, unfoliated pegmatite dyke with gradational (?migmatitic) margins.
Fine to medium grained, green-grey feld-qtz-mag-py gneiss with minor qtz-kspar pegmatitic dykes, minor qtz and minor carb veins. Minor gt associated with mafic veins (?pyroxene).

Possible cross cutting relationship to ?later, pink coarse grained qtz-feld dyke. Unfoliated and equigranular with some red hem fragments and kspar alteration rimming grains. Some thin late hem veins

20cm of pink, coarse grained peg and then fine grained pyroxenitic ?dyke
Complex zone of medium to coarse grained felsic intrusives with blocks of dark grey, fine grained  pyroxene-bearing material. Abundant qtz flooding and act-sulphide veining
Sharp, irregular contact to zone of carbonate flooding. Common, large and small blocks of folded and banded kspar-qtz-(hem-? pyx) gneiss and fine grained  pyx-chl rock

Sheared granite with segregations of kfs+qtz and biotite. Rare zibes if unfoliated massiv quartz/kfs with contacts parallel to shear foliation. Rare leucoxenes near downhole contact.

Massive medium-coarse grained granitoid with irregular quartz veining. Contacts parallel to shear foliation. Downhole contact with 1mm chlorite rim. Patches of biotite/magneite interstitally positioned between qtz/kfs.

Regular distribution of quartz/kfs within biotite/chlorite matrix. Occasional bands of qtz/kfs partial metl(?) intruding along shear foliation. Occasional bands of magnetite parallel to shear foliation.

Massive phlogopite/chlorite rich interval with small blebs of regularly distributed qtz/kfs throughout. Predominantly unfoliated with increase in qtz/kfs and foliated texture downhole. Texturally granitic with less kfs than surrounding rock. no veini

Strongly foliated kfs/qtz-phyric sheared granitic gneiss. Shearing producing incomplete bands of kfs/qtz and bi. Occasional 4-7cm bands of later post/syn defomational qtz/kfs parallel to foliation planes.
Crackled with chlorite/carbonate veining. Carbonate veins with chlorite halos. Lithology still granitic. Sericite alteration adjacent to carbonate veins.

Gradual increase in kf @ uphole cnt. Weakly foliated granitic gneiss with shear texture giving foliation to the rock. Occasional coarse grained kfs/qtz later intrusions parallel to foliation. Coarse grained  intrusives with occasional HRR alteration.

Moderately to strongly shear-foliated kfs-phyric granitic gneiss. Occasional coarse grained kfs/qtz parallel to foliation. Patchy diopside near downhole contact. Partial melt(?) macroveins of kfs/qtz x-cutting foliation. diffuse  downhole contact.
Syntectonic injection of granite with strong foliated texture. Fine grained with considerably less bi than surrounding rocks. Contacts match rock foliation. Zones of MGG between intrusions.

Sheared granitic gneiss with patches/stringers of diopside at low angles to foliation angle. Possibly carbonate veining later sheared and altered(?). Downhole contact paralled to sheared foliation - increased diopside - finer grained kfs.
Extremely coarse grained quartz/kfs pegmatite with clasts of biotite/sericite/diopside included - most likely from country rock. Strong igneous texture. Downhole contact sericitised - broken core.
Strongly foliated quartz-phyric granitic gneiss with occasional intrusives of less foliated kfs>qtz parallel to foliation axis. Highly sericitised/chloritised interval from 298.9-290m

Massive quartz/kfs pegmatite with sparse biotite. Coarser grained and more distinct separation of kfs/qtz at downhole contact. Contacts parallel to foliation plane. faint hint of foliation at uphole contact where kfs/qtz more intercalated.

Moderately foliated sheared granitic gneiss. 20cm Biotite phyric interval with undeformed kfs from 303.5m. Folded macroveins of weakly foliated qtz+kfs subparallel to foliation plane and rare fine grained pegmatitic intervals.

Moderately to well sheared granitic gneiss with dipiside alteration of groundmass and magnetite disseminations throughout. Downhole contact diffuse with pegmatitic unit. Contact sub-parallel to foliation plane.

Very strongly foliated gneissic unit with garnet prophyroblasts throughout. Up and downhole contacts in fine to medium grained quartz/kfs pegmatite(?). Possibly a sedimentary interval based on occurrence of garnet and strong banding.

Weakly foliated to massive  biotite phyric granitoid with even regular distribution of qtz/kfs mottling. Increase in diopside alteration from ~365-~369m. Speckled leucoxees from ~376m to downhole contact. Granite is weakly foliated at downhole contac

Massive medium-coarse grained quartz within predominantly kfs matrix. Rare patches of biotite. Zones of HRR overprinting. Weak sericite alteration along fracture surfaces, late carbonate veining. Downhole contact diffuse with increased sericite alter

Zone of intense alteration and possible sediment rafting. Fluid textures of k-metasomatism - flame alteration patterns. Underlying rock probably granitoid. Possibly a shear with pulses of k-fluids moving through and rafts of sediment being caught up.

bi-phyric granitoid less foliated at margins and increasingly foliated at center. Retrograde crackling of injected coarse graind granite and patches to veins of less deformed granite parallel to foliation. Chlorite veining at an angle to the foliatio

Highly altered shear one with strong sericite/chlorite alteration of potassic core. Possible thin intervals of sedimentary rafting intermingled with the granitoid. Strong sericitised shear at DH contact.
Shear-foliated gneissic granite with unfoliated coarse grained quartz/kfs intrusive in large intervals and small patches. sericite-altered shear planes at downhole contact.

Fine grained metapelite with fgr disseminated py. Regular dark bt rich? laminations.Varyingly pervasive ch alteration with green alteration more siliceous zones. Patchy kf alt qtz blebs/veins. Some quartz veins with variable ch alt. Small blebs of bt

Recrystallised limestone breccia with some remenant bedding. Ch and weak-kf alt of<30mm pelite clasts. Patchy quartz bands former beds? Some fgr ch in cb matrix. Some ch/cb healed fractures.

Recrystallised limestone breccia with ch/kf altered bt/qtz pelite clasts. Weak relic bedding. Fgr ch/kf/bt grains. Some kf altered cb veins.

Foliated ch and kf altered qtz rich fgr psammopelite. Some cb veins with trace fgr py. Zone of exclusive kf altertion ~35cm. Small ch healed fault?

Quartz-pelite banded former dolomite? Pervasive chlorite alt. Small fracture/fault zone. Patchy mgr gn and some similar tabular red minerals. Patchy black tabular amphibole crystals. Patchy kf alt. Some late stage ch alt cb veins.

Calc-silicate skarn altered psammopelite with patchy mt. Extensive cb veins causing minor fracturing. Patchy kf alt. Patchy qtz surrounded by grn ch alt. Patchy fgr amph phenocrysts.

Recrystallised limestone with fgr ch grains and mgr-cgr ch alt bt-pelite breccia clasts. Minor kf alt of cb. Some clasts display remenant bedding.

Pseudobrecciated hematite-altered volcanic. Slighly faulted and healed in place. Magnetite metasomatism altering a large percentage of the rock leaving hm 'clasts'. weak chlorite alteration of magnetite-rich zones.

Variably ch/hm altered volcanic andesite with speckly overprinted/destroyed phenocrysts and variable magnetite content. Fluid alteration textures throughout. Where magnetite has been altered to martite- patches/blebs of massive ang quartz - not amygd
Quartz-filled amygdals in hm/ch atered andesite as previous. Chlorite overprinting Hm (scratch is red). Stressed/fractured core. Weak slickenslides at up and downhole contacts.

Amygdal phyric aphanitic andesite (?) with pervasive hematite alteration. Amygdals uphole are sub-angular - becoming more anguar  downhole. Alteration becoming more light/dark brown downhole - sericitisation?
Strongly magnetite-altered interval with slightly diffuse straight contact with uphole andesite. Downhole contact also diffuse with HS increae near contact. Distinctive py mineralisation in interval.
Diffuse contact with magnetite interval uphole. Phenocrysts pale speckled remenants of plag. Chlorite alteration patchy& surrounded by hm. Rare patches of martite adjacent to quartz blebs.

Less magnetic-interval. Almost no response. Martite in microveins. Patchy/diffuse ch/hm alteration. Very rare fl+qtz nodules.Hm-alteration is lighter red than uphole. Possibly potassic? Microveining gives almost crackled appearance.
Darker red shade from previous interval Texturally similar. microveins are absent and magnetite is associated with chlorite-altered patches.

Pervasively chlorite altered interval. Amygdaloidal with quartz-filled amyg's. Pseudobrecciated from variably ch/hm alteration patches - pheno's visible in both. Ch overprinting hm. Breccia-veined with cpy/qtz.

Mottled interval with small unaltered circles surrounded by dark read earthy heatite. Core surface is pitted and has considerably greater topography than elsewhere. Rare Hrr/Hre>Hs veining. Possibly stressed/faulted/miled and healed?
Continuation of mottled interval with increaed hre banding/veining.Patches of chlorite and rare veins of martite.
Magnetite pseudo breccia with large 'clasts' of hematite-altered andesite.Contacts not measured in struct - best guess is steeply dipping north-northeast - 15-20 degrees north? 50 degree dip?

diffuse contact with uphole magnetite-rich interval. Aphanitic hematite-altered andesite(?) with weak mottling/patching of ch/hm.patches of hrr in blebs/veins increasing downhole. Veins rimmed with martite halo.

Porphyritic plagioclase andesite with plag phenos altered with HRR (potassium?) and quartz-filled amygdals. Distinctive unit with textures/mineralogy preserved. Fractures infilled with chlorite. Faulted upper and lower contacts with clear slickenslid

medium to poorly sorted sublitharenitic sandstone - probably of volcanic protolith. Crosscut by fractured/brecciated qtz+cb veining. Crosscut by later carbonate veining. Faulted downhole contact with vsl
Weakly foliated volcanic siltstone with zones of coarse grained cross-cutting brecciated(?) quartz+hs+ch+hm. intrusives?

medium to poorly sorted sublitharenitic sandstone - probably of volcanic protolith. Crosscut by fractured/brecciated qtz+cb veining. Crosscut by later carbonate veining. Faulted up and downhole contacts

Weakly foliated to bedded volcanic siltstone with occasional bands of sericite alteration associated with weak fracturing. Foliation/bedding defined by hm<->ch alteration. Weak reverse flaser bedding pattern with vss lenses.
Polymictic breccia of siltstone+sandstone and volcanic clasts. Average clast size is 1.5-2cm. Angular. Crosscutting foliation of vsl uphole.
foliated and bedded hm<->ch altered siltstone with occasional zones of massive siltstone and 30cm zones of sandtone as above. Occasionally interbedded with sandstone rather than ch-altered layers.
Interbedded hm/ch-altered siltstone and medium grained lithic sandstone. Some zones of patchy ss/ssl with weak syn-sed fault patterns.

Flaser-bedded siltstone and sandstone with variable/patchy chlorite alteration. quartz crackle-veining and occasional blebs of quartz. Where faulted quartz is in rounded aggregates. Fissile parallel to bedding.
Chlorite/sericite banded/altered volcanic siltstone with pervasive hematite alteration and small patches of siltstone. Crackle veined with Hs/HRE infill.

Significant reduction in hematite alteration. Sandstone beds light grey interbedded with chlorite green siltstone beds. Syn sedimentary deformation structures. Crosscut by fractured quartz/hm/ch veining. Occasional patches of angular martite-frac cnt
Variably hm/ch altered volcnic sandstone with large patches of each diffusely intercalated with one another. Very weak assosication of hematite with magnetite micro/crackle veining throughout unit.
Polymict breccia with variable ch and hm and mr altered vss/vsl. Ch+ Mr and Hs infill.
Syn-sed structures in bedded highly-altered siltstone to sandstone. Fracturing/faulting perpendictular to bedding with martite/magnetite alteration alone cracks.
Pervasively hm-altered siltstone with texturally destructive hm alteration in some areas and rare sericite alteration. Martite/magnetite veining and rare patches of martite. Microveined with calcite.

Small chloritic breccia at uphole contact. Other brecciate intervals downhole with fractured quartz veins and chlorite/sericite alteration. Patches of martite adjacent to quartz veining. Magnetite veining throughout.
Diffusely variably hm/ch altered sandstone. patches of green/ppl varying throughout. Rare magnetite veining.
Macroveins of fractured quartz+martite+chlorite+specular hemattie+pyrite+chalcopyrite sub parallel to core axis.
Fine grained volcanic sandstone with pervasive chlorite alteration and rare blebs of quartz and hs. qtz/hs does not appear to be veined and sandstone is not faulted.
Possible faulted uphole contact - contact lost but weak slickenslides on siltstone. Thinly bedded siltstone with pervasive hematite alteration. Fractured quartz/ch macro veining from 570.9-573.8m
Fault zone through previous interval. broken core parallel to bedding.
Bedded siltstone as per pervious unit with slighly chlorite alteration of alternating beds. Rare macroveins of fractured quartz.
Macrovein subparallel to core axis through previous unit. Martite+specular hematite+quartz+py in vein. Weak contact metamorphism halo adjacent to vein.
Bedded siltstone with slight chlorite alteration of alternating beds. Rare fractured quartz macroveining.
Weakly brecciated/stressed interval with slickenslides running sub-parallel to core axis. Fractured quartz/hematite veining.
Massive to bedded dark grey chlorite altered (perhaps reduced and unaltered?) siltstone. Downhole contact slightly hematite altered and perpendicular to core axis.
Massive to bedded grey/green chlorite-altered siltstone with weak sericite alteration near base. Rare quartz/sericite macro veining. EOH

Basement. Pink. Fizzes with 10% HCl.
Pinkish grey dolomitic unit with styolitic textures and carbonate veining. vuggy porosity throughout - especially prevalent in cb-veining.
Conformable andesitic flow. Very fine grained at up and downhole contacts. Appears to have been overturned based on uphole contact. Microveins of quartz/carbonate with hematite alteration halos.
More strongly hm-altered dolomitic limestone. Silicified with weak styolitic textures and vuggy porosity. Vugs concentrated in carbonate veining. surfaces of vugs appear to be coated with ankerite.
Transition zone from hm-altered dolomite to ch-altered dolomite. Reduction in vuggy porosity increase in styolitic texture and silicification.

Less dolomitic than previous interval. Very weakly bedded ch-altered dolomite with bedding defined by alternating hm/ch-altered bands at a medium-steep angle to core axis. Strong styolitic textures with undissolved ch.

Less altered dolomite with bedding defined by bands of hematite-altered carbonate and varying purity of limestone. Slightly siliceous. Slightly less dolomitic. Styolites contain concentrated chlorite.  patches of light pink ankerite common assoc w st

Massive very fine grained limestone/dolomite. Weak reaction with hcl- stronger when scratched. Crosscut by unaltered carbonate veins. Styolitic textures with no infill. Irregular bands and patches of pink ankerite/carbonate.
Faintly appararent bedding in very fine grained and relatively unaltered dolomite. Styolites clearly defined with chlorite infill. Crosscut with veins of light pink carbonate/ankerite.
white/brown bedding horizons in very fine grained dolomite. Weak HCl reaction. Crosscut with veins and crackle veins of pink carbonate. Styolites common with varible chlorite/no infill.
Very strong crackle brecciation of dolomite with hematite-alteration exploiting fracture and veins, crosscutting styolites with occasional chlorite infill.
Light green and pink dolomite with chlorite undesolved in styolites. Gradual reduction in crackle texture at uphole contact. Downhole contact increasing in crackle again.
Medium red crackled silicified dolomite with chlorite-filled styolites. porosity possibly primary due to sparry cement growing perpendicular to the free surface.
Light brown/green silicified dolomote. Chlorite throughout and in styolitic concentrations. Light brown colour possibly due to siderite(?)

Patchy/laminated highly silicified dolomite(?) with intense siderite(?) alteration giving brown/green colour. Patchy/diffuse uphole and downhole contact with paler white/brown dolomite. Less reactive to HCL than paler units. Late carbonate veining
Variably siderite/chlorite-altered, highly silicified dolomite. Rare porosity with sparry cement. Chlorite also concentrated in styolites.
Porosity weakly fenestrate and localised in small patches possibly primary due to development of sparry cement.

Patchy/laminated highly silicified dolomite(?) with intense siderite(?) alteration giving brown/green colour. Patchy/diffuse uphole and downhole contact with paler white/brown dolomite. Less reactive to HCL than paler units. Late carbonate veining
Weakly chlorite altered silicified dolomite with chlorite concentrated in styolites and disseminated throughout.

Patchy/laminated highly silicified dolomite(?) with intense siderite(?) alteration giving brown/green colour. Patchy/diffuse uphole and downhole contact with paler white/brown dolomite. Less reactive to HCL than paler units. Late carbonate veining
Variably chlorite<->siderite<->hematite-altered silicious dolomite with occasional weak laminations and possible bedding.
Purple/brown/green/white beds of silicified dolomote (jasperoid/siderite/chlorite impurities(?) bedded perpendicular to core axis.
Ploymictic breccia in silicified dolomite host. Clasts are highly silicified iron-altered bedded mudstone(?)/quartz/specular hematite. Clasts are angular and .5-1cm.
Faulted uphole contact with slickenslides. Massive coarse grained granite with sericite alteration and phlogopite dispersed around coarse grained kfs>qtz.
Aphanitic intrusive. Chilled margins are slightly yellow. Phenocrysts do not recuce in size at margin - crysts were developped prior to intrusion? Groundmass has a rapidly chilled texture.
Massive coarse grained granite as previously described with slightly less sericitic alteration.

Slightly coarser grained groundmass than previous intrusive, possibly of andesitic composition. Magnetic response at up and downhole contacts - rapid chilling of iron? Weak crackle of carbonate veining.

Sheared and strained core Milled clasts of kfs in predominantly graphite +biotite +fgr qtz. Compotent with slickenslides and sections of massive graphite.
Bedded bi/grp and quartz metapelite. Non-graphitic zones show biotite altered to k-fs, probably metasomatic.
Massive metasomatite, possible psammite protolith with nearly complete metasomatism. The Texture is not igneous but a partial replacement of what was likely massive quartzite.
Disrupted beds of hm/ch altered metasediment interbedded with graphite/biotite/quartz. Rare brecciated patches of diopside alteration adjacent to faces with slickenslide.

Metasomatic alteration of above metapelite. Original texture of rock is preserved, alkali metasomatism altering former dark layers, quartz beds remain unaltered. Later partial sericite alteration of metasomatised beds. Zones of mottled qtz/kfs - psam
Bedded graphitic quartz/kfs/bi/graph metsediment, shear planes with graphitic slickenslides. Strained core with disrupted beds
Massive quartz/kfs metasomatite with quasai igneous texture. Most likely massive pelite with alkali fluids metasomatically altering the rock, incomplete alteration.

Broken core at uphole contact with fault zone. Massive quartz/kfs metasomatite with quasai igneous texture. Most likely massive pelite with alkali fluids metasomatically altering the rock, incomplete alteration.
Massive psammite interbedded with quartz/graphite psammite.
Massive quartz/kfs metasomatite with quasai igneous texture. Most likely massive pelite with alkali fluids metasomatically altering the rock, incomplete alteration.

Biotite/chlorite-altered metasediment with disseminated graphite. Rare zones of sericite alteration. interbedded with finegrained quartzite. Thin fault gauge at top downhole contact, Possibly faulted uhole contact in broken core.

Foliated metasomatite preserving original rock texture with bands of quartz and alkali alteration and speckled biotite. rare sericite alteration of kfs-altered beds.
Selectively hm>ch-altered metasediment, bedded with large carbonate veining. disrupted beds with small-scale faulting

Bedded, selectively hm>ch-altered seletive with occasional veins of kfs an occasional carbonate macroveins. Faulted/milled clayey downhole contact

Interbedded limestone and sand/siltstone. Beds contain angular clasts of ch-altered siltstone. Possibly poor sorting during deposition(?) Some beds parallel to the boundaries of larger clasts, dropstones(?). Carbonate and ankerite microveining.
Dolomitic silt/sandstone. beded with weak chlorite alteration throughout. Ankerite and carbonate veining. Some hematite-altered beds. Uphole and downhole contacts are parallel to bedding.
Variably chlrorite and hematite altered limestone with weak synsedimentary textures and rare massive sandstone horizons. 6cm clayey fault zone from 790.2m

Variably hematite<chlorite altered sandstone. Massive and bedded intervals. Contacts parallel to bedding. Thin horizons of bedded limestone as previous. Faulted ankerite veins and later unfractured carbonate veins. EOH/.

Interval of decreased magnetite alteration. Predominantly red/brown hematite (k?)-altered volcanic with speckled leucoxenes. Zones of ch>mt alteration. Bands of concentrated apatite and chalcopyrite with indistinct edges - veins?

Leucoxene phyric interval of aphanitic intermediate volcanic. Weak hematite alteration with pervasie magnetite alteration throughout. Downhole contact diffuse with onset of large apatite zones.
Pseudobrecciated interval of large hm-stained apatite patches white patches of albite and grey fine grained magnetite infill. GH CNT at appearance of amygdals - Contact looks like an overturned flow.
Massive amygdaloidal basaltic unit with amygdales rimmed with HRR halos. 'Veins' of magnetite cutting the volcanic beginning the replacement seen uphole. DH contact as amygdales subside.

Massive aphanitic basaltic unit. Pervasive hematite alteration being replaced by partial magnetite alteration - veins cross cutting and replacing. Rare patches of apatite suggest earlier potassic alteration.Leucoxene phyric.

Uphole contact lost in texturally destructive hm/mt metasomatistm. 1-2mm tabular plagioclase phenocrysts hm-altered. Pervasive mt but less visible than in above intervals. Visually similar to basaltic andesites uphole. Autobrecciated downhole contact
Increase in phenocryst grain size of plagioclase. 3-4mm tabular plagioclase altered to chlorite. Autobrecciated downhole contact.

Very fine grained sandstone to siltstone. Hematite-altered with intervals of very faint bedding evident by bands of hm/ch-alteration and bands of unaltered grey silt/sand. Grain size variation too fine to distinguish facing dirs. Rare 2cm patches of
Faulted up and downhole contacts into/out of very fine grained andesitic volcanic. HRR-altered plagioclase phenocrysts - distinguishable @50x.

Massive strongly hematite-altered siltstone with rare intervals of visible bedding. Rare sandier interbeds again grain size variation is too small to determine facing directions. Faulted uphole contact.
Very fine grained mafic/intermediate intrusive. Contacts are sub-vertical.

Bedded hematite-altered siltstone with variable chlorite alteration. Light grey interbeds of slightly increased grain size to vfg sand. Too fine for facing direction. Bedding sub-parallel to core axis.

Intrusive of andesitic composition. hm-altered plagioclase laths visible. Magnetite disseminated throughout - not visibe. Sub-vertical up and downhole contacts. Thin interval of siltstone near DH contact.

Bedded hematite-altered siltstone with variable chlorite alteration. Light grey interbeds of slightly increased grain size to vfg sand. Too fine for facing direction. Bedding sub-parallel to core axis.

Massive fine to medium grained quartz phlogopite amphibolite. Amph is gry/green/yellow. downhole contact is distinct and dipping steeply east - possibly passed through hinge zone.
Moderately to well folate garnet phlogopite gneiss with intervals of massive quartz pegmatite where quartz is green-tinted. Rare patches of fine grained amphibolite.
Well foliated quartz-phyric qtz/ph gneiss. Phlogopite not forming complete bands. Garnet is not present. Downhole contact diffuse with increasing blebby quartz content.
Predominantly green/grey quartz and white/pink fs pegmatite with zones of phlogopite quartz gneiss as previously described.
Foliated but not banded garnet phlogopite quartz gneiss as previous.
Massive coarse grained pegmatite. Quartz is variably grey/green. Patches of phlogopite. Diffuse contacts from metamorphism. Irregular crystal habits.
Well foliated quartz rich phlogopite gneiss. Strong foliation of phlogopite but not banded. No visible garnet. Contact diffuse against pegmatite.
Massive coarse grained pegmatite. Quartz is variably grey/green. Patches of phlogopite. Diffuse contacts from metamorphism. Irregular crystal habits.

Fine grained garnet quartz phlogopite gneiss. Predominantly quartz-phyric with patches of increased garnet and thin horizons of fine grained amphibolite as previously described. Increased thickness of quartz bands downhole. Thicker bands becoming gre

Phlogopite-rich garnet quartz gneiss. Considerably reduced quartz from previous interval Garnet porphyroblasts up to 5mm. Small intervals of amphibole and pegmatite as previously described. Downhole contact defined by increase in quartz.
Medium grined garnet quartz phlogopite gneiss. Coarse grained garnet porphyroblasts. Quartz phyric with large lenses of quartz within bands. Rare intervls of coarse grained pegmatite.
Medium-fine grained quratz phlogopite amphibolite as previous. Diffuse but discernable contacts.
Foliated quartz phlogopite gneiss with 1-3mm garnet porphyroblasts. Up and downhole contacts parallel to foliation.
Sheared quartz in  predominantlu chlorite matrix. Variably brecciated. Shearing parallel to foliation in rock. Milled rounded clasts and angular clasts.
Massive quartz feldspar. Anhedral crystals with strong graphic texture.
Weakly foliated medium grained amphibolite - composition as previously described with increased grain size showing cleavage of amphiboles.
Foliated to banded quartz-phyric garnet phlogopite quartz gneiss as previous. Minor lenticular quartz blebs in bands. Rare pegmatitic patches. EOH.
Fine oxidised orange/brown/yellow silt
Moderately sorted subrounded medium quartzwith some silt throughout.
Poorly sorted angular-subrounded quartz with fone white silt. Minor pink feldspar lithics. Black round lithics possible amphibole? Possible u/h contamination
Intense hm altered silt in diamict. Some medium grains of sub-angular-subrounded quartz.
No sample taken

Fine grained massive biotite with pervasive chlorite alteration. <1mm carbonate filled crackle veining. Patchy rusty brown very fine grained clayey alteration mineral - looks saprolitic. Chlorite alteration more intense along possibly altered veins.
Fine to medium grained ch/bi altered ampibolite. Carbonate fille cackle microveining and pervasive magnetite throughout. Light/rusty brown alteration along fractures.

metasediment - possibly ampibolite. Strongly and pervasively altered by very fine grained clayey/waxy light brown/rusty red alt min possibly pseudomorphing amph. Biotite supported by brown mineral. Patches of bi/cb intergrowths psu-exsolution. Cb-vei
Massive granular biotite amphibolite with rare pyroxene crystals occuring in discrete patches. Pervsive light yellow/green chlorite alteration/weathering.
Continuation of previous interval with slightly increased grain size.
1cm+ black amphibole crystals with patches of quratz and chlorite between crysts. Very rare biotite - amph makes up at least 85% of the rock.
Finer grined version of previous interval. amph crystals are ~1-2mm evenly dispersed with quartz and chlorite.
Massive coarse grained quartz/kfs pegmatite with green and grey quartz. Grain boundaries anhedral from subsequent metamorphism. Interstital chlorite. Sharp UH contact. Downhole contact diffuse.

Massive medium-coarse grained amphibolite as previously described. Amph grains up to 3mm. Interstital ch and fgr qtz. Rare zones with speckled phlogopite becoming more frequent downhole. Discernable but diffuse downhole contact.
Massive coarse grained quartz/kfs pegmatite as previous with chunks of highly chloritised metased as xenoliths from host rock.

Strongly interclated pegmatite and medium grained chlorite-biotite metasediment - likely retrograde from amphibolite based on pseudomorphing alteration minerals. Coarse grained retrograde clinopyroxene (big guess) pseudomorphed by brn clayey min @ 10

Medium to fine grained biotite quartz amphibolite as previously described. Zones of weak foliation. Patches to thin intervals of green and pink quartz/kfs pegmatite (as prev.) with adjacent retrograde px(?)(also as prev).Irregular/diffuse contacts/

Fine grained silicified metased. Some quartz possibly pseudomorphing fine grained amphibole. Disseminated unfoliated biotite.Quartz has pale green/grey colouring. Contacts show rapid increase/decrease in quartz content.

Very fine grained quartz-rich biotite amphibolite(?). Amphibole(?) replaced by light brown amorphous alteration mineral - siderite? Very rare isolated garnet porph.blasts. possible finely disseminated graphite(?). Ch/Bi microveins.
Continuation of previous unit. Weakly foliated and mica is predominantly phlogopite. Indistinct downhole contact with increase in quartz content and decrease in brown alt. mineral.
Massive medium-coare rained pegmatite as previously described. Grey/green quartz and pink feldspar. Anhedral crystals from metamorphism. Downhole contact diffuse.

70%+ graphite with weak shear textures near uphole contact - becoming less pronounced downhole. Graphite possibly replacing/pseudomorphing phlogopite based on morphology. Irregular shaped patches of frac'd qtz with grp veinlets. Grp is likely hydroth
Increased qtz/kfs at uh contact - lesser kfs throughout. Massive medium-coarse grained amphibolite (?) with quartz replacing amph. Graphite and lesser phlogopite in void space. Chlorite microveins.
Massive fine grained metasediment with zones/patches of intercalated  chlorite/quartz/biotite. Variably disseminated graphite becoming graphite-rich near DH contact.
Weakly foliated to massive chlorite/magnetite-rich amphibolite (or retrograde dyke?). Speckled quartz throughout with rare disseminated graphite. Micas concentrated adjacent to sulphide veining.
Strongly chlorite altered amphibolite. Irregular bands/patches of phlogopite. Chlorite alteration front drops out at highly chloritised clayey fault plane.

Massive fine to medium grained amphibolite as previously described. Weak pervasive chlorite alteration and 1-2mm chlorite veining. Steeply north-dipping east-west downhole conact with massive chlorite at boundary.
Massive recrystallised limestone with ~30% speckled chlorite. Chlorite in subrounded medium-coarse grained patches. Best guess at protolith is a calcareous arkosic sandstone.
Massive fine grained quartz chlorite metasediment. 3-4mm laminated sericite carbonate-filled angular fracture runnining sub-parallel to core. Vein is truncated at DH and UH contacts.
Massive chlorite-speckled recrystallised limestone as previous. Rare patches of phlogopite.
Recrystallised limestone with mgr subrounded/subangular chlorite as previous. Rare patches where magnetite is replacing the chlorite. No visible veinlet where iron fluid might have infiltrated.
Continuation of previous unit with increased magnetite alteration. Chlorite is much paler green and much softer - possibly sericite?
Rcrystallised calcite with subrounded/subangular mgr chlorite as previous. Variable green shading of chlorite - percentage consistent. Very rare patches of magnetite.

Recrystallised limestone as previous with speckled chlorite with sandy habit. Variable green/grey colour of altered sandy grains. Occasional zones with 3-5cm chlorite patches and mottled phlogopite. Irregular quartz blebs. Increased %ch from previous

Intercalated silicified calcite/dolomite with pervasive chlorite alteration. Patchy sericite alteration. Rare coarser grained micaceous patches - micaceous uphole contact. Sericitised downhole contact.
Recrystallised calcite as previous with green alteration now predominantly sericite. Phlogopite in small patches and disseminated throughout.

Massive medium-fine grained phlogopite chlorite metasediment. patches of massive sericite and patches of carbonate. Blebs of quartz with phlogopite rims becoming more chloritic and more sericitic moving away from the center.
Massive recrystallised limestone with granular subrounded/subangular sericite as previously described. Sharp up and downhole contacts with band of phogopite,.
Medium grained quartz biotite skarn or retrograde amphibolite - amph->bi. Disseminated pyrite throughout.
Massive quartz biotite metapelite as previously described but missing the quartz component. Possible fault zone from 396.7-397.1.
Recrystallised granular chlorite limestone as previously described.

Massive quartz/biotite metasediment with weak pervasive chlorite alteration.Strong interlocking texture - possibly retrograde metamorphism from amphibolite or even a dyke. Sharp up and downhole contacts with good contrast against limestone and mic

Granular chlorite reXtalised limestone wih patchy phlogopite as previous. Rare small zones where the subrounded grains are magnetite. Magnetite appears to be fracture controlled with fractures healed through recrystallisation of calcite.
Massive biotite chlorite metasediment with interstitial carbonate. Diffuse up and downhole contacts. Uphole contact most gradual.
Massive sericite/recrystallised carbonate as previous. Occasional blue sericite grains. Carbonate is becoming more dolomitic from previous intervals.
Massive to randomly foliated silicified chlorite/biotite metasediment. Foliations are similar to botroydal texture only on the scale of 5-12cm.
Recrystallised carbonate as previous. Contacts well defined by bands of biotite rich metasediments.
Strongly sericite altered interval - bands of phlogopite/carbonate quartz and sericite.
Recrystallised carbonate as previous. Interval of phlogopite metased running parallel to the core.
Intercalated patchy quartz/biotite schist/gneiss  +massive chlorite + medium grained randomly oriented biotite.
Massive recrystallised limestone as previous. Patches of chlorite and patches of biotite.

Predominantly moderately foliated quartz/biotite gneiss with pervasive chlorite alteration. Thin intervals of recrystallised limestone/chlorite as previous. Thin intervals of massive mgr foliated biotite.30cm fault zone from 439.1m
Massive granular medium grained quartz biotite/phlogopite gneiss. biotite grains randomly oriented. Discernable contact plane although contact itself is diffuse.\
Massive medium grained recrystallised limestone with variably chlorite/sericite altered grains and patchy phlogopite.
Massive biotite>quartz pelite at up and downhoe contacts. Moderately diffuse change to patchy sericite and pervasive chlorite-altered silicified dolomite towards center of interval
Up to 60% chlorite in recrystallised chlorite/ recrystallisedcarbonate as previously described
Brecciated clasts of biotite/chlorite pelite in recrystallised limestone matrix. pervasive sericite in carbonate near downhole contact.
Variably sericite/chlorite altered grains in recrystallised limestone/dolomite as previous. Zones of patchy phlogopite and/or chlorite.

Prodominantly massive sericite/quartz metapelite intercalated with patchy phlogopite.Late calcite macroveins exploiting phlogopite-rich intervals. Possible actinolite in some strongly sericite-altered regions - possibly in a former vein.
Massive recrystallised limestone with granular chlorite as prev.
Massive fine grained biotite gneiss or possibly a diorite based on strongly interlocking crystals. Check geochem,

Folliated brecciated clasts of biotite/chlorite/quartz pelite. Clasts up to 12 cm. Smaller clasts are folliated regularly throughout interval and suspended in recrystallised limestone. Clasts are not granular or subrounded as in previous SLM downhole
Massive recrystallised limestone as previous with subangular to angular clasts of chlorite -up to 3mm- speckled throughout.
Massive fine grained sericite with soft chlorite pseudomorphing actinolite or possibly tremolite veining.
Patches to bands of massive randomly oriented phlogopite in recrystallised limestone with angular to subangular 1-3mm clasts of chlorite as previous.
Massive coarse grained sericite pseudomorphing actinolite (? - retrograde?) Zones of mottle quartz>>biotite granitoid(?)

Massive to weakly foliated recrystallised limestone with subrounded to subangular chlorite clasts throughout. Patches of massive randomly foliated phlogopite. Blebs of quartz with symmetric halos: qtz->thin ch -> radiating mica -> se -> thick ch @ 61
Medium grained randomly oriented biotite forming weakly foliated bands with interstitial quartz and carbonate. sharp up and downhole contacts with onset of dark micas.
Intensely deformed intercalated quartz/phlogopite/fluorite metasediment(?) or possible deformed vein (?) Patch of coarse grained retrograde actinolite/tremolite(?) as previous.
Massive recrystallised limestone with mottled speckled chlorite in subrounded/subangular granular habit as prev. Patches of phlogopite as previously described.

Massive leucocratic coarse grained quartz-phyric granitoid with possible very coarse grained actinolite crystals at random orientations. Patchy sericite/chlorite veining. Patches of pervasiely se-altered silicified carbonate.
Recrystallised limestone with speckled chlorite grains as previously described. Patches of rand. oriented phlogopite with intersitial carbonate as previous. EOH
Red oxidised soil after siltstone
White siltstones
Red siltstones
Orange siltstones
Transition zone from Orange siltstone to black shales
Black shales with minor red lithics from uphole contamination
Grey, black qtz sands with abundant red lithics from uphole contamination. Possible mica - unclear if diamictite or basement.
No Samples
Possible basement or diamictite biotite + qtz + pink feldspar.
Strongly foliated micaceous schist with porphyroblastic growths of quartz and kfs parallel to bedding/foliation of rock. Occasional macroveining of quartz and Kspar. Rare small garnet porphyroblasts.

Strongly foliated/bedded micaceous phyllite with selective alteration of beds by hematite. Interbedded wi9th magnetite. Foliations dipping steeply north. Clay-healed shear running steeper than bedding along core axis at 147.3. Very fissile parallel t
Micaceous phyllite. medium-fine grained muica strongly foliated parallel to bedding. Interbedded with magnetite in roughly equal portions. Extremely fissile along foliation/bedding planes.

Phyllite as previously described with hematite-alteration along selective beds. Very low-angle folding along core axis. Weak ch-altered faiult at uphole contact. Broken core above uphole contact - unclear if folded surrounding fault.

Phyllite as previously described with quartz/hematite/kfs macroveining running sub-parallel to bedding (slighly crosscutting) with patchy magnetite in the veins as well. Foliations still steeply north dipping. Weak hematite-alteration of some beds.
short-throw faults assoc with qtz veins. Patchy mt in qtz veins.

Increased mica from previous interval with visible development of crenulation cleavage trending northwest-southeast. Beds are predominantly folded with microfolds mirroring crenulation direction. (W-shapes on NW-quadrant.)

Massive quartz with contacts parallel to bedding. Quartz does not appear to be metasedimentary - massive habbit with no visible grains. Surface is stressed/crackled. ca +/- magnetite stringers - possibly picked up during injection of quartz.

Foliated mica and magnetite phyllite with folded and deformed beds and weak crenulation cleavage. Selective alteration of some beds by hematite. Foliations/bedding still predominantly dipping steeply northwards.

Massive quartz with similar stressed/surface fractured appearance as previous with microveins of mica/chlorite parallel to surrounding foliation. Kfs-alt at up and downhole contacts. contacts parallel to foliation.

Foliated to bedded magnetite phyllite with selective hematite-alteration of some beds. Areas of increase HM alteration do not contain magnetite or contain significantly less than unaltered magnetite bands.
Magnetite phyllite as previously described with less hematite alteration and increased magnetite bedding. Occasional quartz+/- ch +kfs veins running parallel to bedding.

Folded interval - fold striking northeast/southwest. This interval consists of a complete S-fold with quartz veining in the convace sides of the fold and mica/mt forming the convex side. Strong crenulation of micas adjacent to quartz.
Magnetite phyllite as previously described with occasional quartz kfs+/-tremolite veins. Visible crenulation cleavage at a high angle to bedding.
Predominantly quartz with thin stringers of muscovite. patchy kfs. magnetite and chlorite in blocky habits.
Bedded and crenulated magnetite phyllite. Rare veins of quartz and kfs +/- tr and ch with contacts parallel to foliations but not completely cutting core. Crenulations are generally south-dipping.
Broken core predominantly chlorite and muscovite with rare magnetite in fault zone to 298m. Downhole of interval core is stressed and weakly fracture with chlorite infill.

Foliated and bedded magnetite phyllite as previously described. weak hematite alteration of some beds and rare thin quartz/kfs veining. Folding not as prevelent in this interval. Crenulation cleavage at high angle to bedding.
Weak fault zone through previous unit with chlorite clays on fractured surfaces. Predominantly broken core with weak stress fracturing of the beds.

Magnetite phyllite as previously desctribed with varying thickness of magnetite bands and occasional quartz kfs veining. Biotite in quartz veins being altered to chlorite. Veining weakly coincides with folding of beds.
Fault zone through previous interval in a zone where magnetite is not present. Chlorite healed fractured/stressed core.

Banded magnetite phyllite as previous with varying mt/mu ratios. Folding more frequent and intense with small s-folds visible throughout. Foliations varying between very steep north and south-dipping. Occasional quartz veining as previously described
Brecciated clasts of hm/mt-altered pelite preserving folded texture. Subrounded clasts of quartz. Muscovite and chlorite infill. Fault is dipping moderatly to the south.
Compotent interval between faulted intervals. Strongly hematite/magnetite altered psammite(?) with weak foliations. Crosscutting carbonate veins
Intercalated hematite/magnetite-altered psammite(?) with foliatioms dipping steeply north. Cross cutting the psammite bedding/foliation is muscovite with foliations roughly parallel to the psammite.
Milled sub-rounded clasts of hematite / magnetite altered psammite within chlorite infill with rare patches of muuschovite.

Magnetite phyllite as previously described. Moderate to strong fold textures. Weak to moderate hematite alteration of magneite bands stronger at edges. Weak crenulation of muscovite. Rare qtz/ veins. Foliations generally north/northwest dipping.
Brecciated clasts of hematite-altered psammite with rare magnetite alteration within chlorite/muscovite matrix. Matrix supported clasts.
Magnetite phyllite as previous with less defined to absent crenulation. Weak hematite alteration of some magnetite beds. Quartz/kfs microveins cross cutting foliation.
Very steep south-dipping fault breccia with clasts of hm-altered pelite rare magnetite and some carbonate infill. Predominantly ch/mu infill.

Increased hematite alteration of magnetite beds from previous interval. Interbedding of magnetite and mica becoming more regular and even. Beds are Dipping more shallowly to the north. Possibly becoming more schistoise.

Biotite quartz schist with thin bands of magnetite with partial to complete HRR alteration. Veinins of HRR cross cutting foliations and beginning to overprint entire rock in some regions - preferentially replacing magnetite. Psammite interval @ DH Cn

Strongly sericite-metasomatised interval. Replacement of biotite/muscovite beds with sericite. Abundant macroveining.Magnetite bands altered to fine grained magnetite with clays. Patchy kfs possibly also metasomatic - appears to be altering specific
Moderately well fvoliated quartz biotite schist with pervaseive weak sericite alteration. Carbonate macroveining with patchy chalcopyrite near base of interval. HRRalt in discrete intervals.
Clay-milled fault zone.

Fine grained foliated quartz biotite schist. with pervasive weak sericite alteration. KFS and quartz veining. Stronger sericite alteration around quartz veining. Patches of HRR alteration around small fractures.
Increased grain size from previous interval and reduced sericite alteration. HRR alteration still preset along fractures. Foliations still steeply north-dipping

Strongly metasomatised fractured schist. HRR alteration around fractures cross cutting foliation. Patches of ualtered quartz bitite schist as previously described. Sericite alteration is texturally destructive. Slickenslides on broken faces.
Quartz biotite schist as previous with slight increase in size of quartz porphyroblasts. Fractures crosscutting foliation with HRR alteration halos. Some slight boudinage textures on quartz blasts.

Foliated quartz biotite schist with increased quartz content from previous interval. Slight boudinaged texture of porphyroblasts. Slightly strained/fractured at downhole contact. Fractures rarely contain HRR - often carbonate.
Fault zone through previous interval. Predominantly broken core with a thin clayey interval near the center of the interval.
Quartz porphyroblastic schist with extensive biotite. Weak sericite alteration thrughout. Zones of magnetite alteration in discret banded intervals.
Massive to weakly foliated brecciated quartz and biotite metapelite. Variable strong sericite/hm/dolomite infilling clasts/ Faulted downhole contact.

Finely foliated quartz biotite schist with patchy sericite alteration near uphole contact. Short intervals of brecciated schist within recrystallised dolomite. Hematite-altered microveining crosscutting foliations. Wavy foliations from 714m
Diffuse uphole contact with fine grained schist. Brecciated variably hm-altered clasts of schist in recrystallised hm-altered dolomite.

Finely foliated quartz biotite schist with wavy foliations. Diffuse up and downhole contacts. Small scale brecciation in some interavals. Patchy carbonate (dolomite) infill of fractures. Quartz porphyroblasts and rare qartz veining.
Diffuse uphole contact with fine grained schist. Brecciated variably hm-altered clasts of schist in recrystallised hm-altered dolomite.
Predominantly quartz biotite schist with sub-vertical foliations fine grained quartz porphyroblasts and weak hematite alteration. Diffuse downhole contact.,
Variably hematite altered schist within recrystalised dolomite.
Red oxidised siltstone containing saprolite lithics and some silty lithics.
Purple/white siltstone with saprolite lithics
Orange siltstone with significant lithics
Fine purple siltstone
Orange/brown silt increasing in colour intensity downhole
Fine purple/brown silt
Fine red silt
Light purple/yellow silt
Fine yellow silt
Fine yellow/grey silt
Fine dark shale
Well sorted angular to subrounded grey quartz. Some red feldspar lithics. Slight increase in grain size downhole
Silty diamict containing quartz, feldspar and muscovite lithics.
Basement, containing magnetite, silty and possible feldspar lithics
Finely laminated slate/phyllite with strong chlorite alteration of alternating beds. Highly fissile in addition to fissility derived from chlorte interbeds. Possible weak shear textures.

Interbedded limestone and fine grained siltstone. Limestone is medium grained and likely recrystallised. Boudinaged siltstone lenses. microfaults at high angles ~80 degrees to shear foliation giving weak cs fabric.
milled clayey shear zone - shearing parallel to main shear foliation uphole interval. clasts of subrounded to angular quartz with patchy calcite. Broken DH contat.
Interbedded and sheared medium-fine grained recrystallised calcite and friable weakly chlorite altered shale/slate. boudinaged quartz lenses with long axis parallel to shear direction.
Friable very fine grained slate with eggshell lustre on clean broken faces. Weak chlorite alteration on some cleavage planes.

Sheared interbedded limestone and very fine grained reduced siltstone with weak chlorite alteration as previous. Shear foliation dipping steeply to the north. Decrease in calcite and increase in fissility near downhole contact.
Predominantly broken core through black slate/phyllite. Broken faces more lustrous than previous fault zone. Very low graphitic content near downhole contact.
Interbedded reduced siltstone with weak chlorite alteration and sandy dolomite. sheared as previous with boudinaged to brecciated siltstone.

Alternating bands of hm/k(?) altered very fine grained pelite and diopside-altered carbonate. Likely a metasomatised version of the previous interval without shearing. Foliation of extensional faulting (overturned) dipping shallowly S. SDO infill wit

very fine grained laminated schist/slate with one cleavage direction parallel to foliation (~45 degrees to core axis) and a second strong cleavage at 70-80 degrees to the first. Regular k-altered microveins parallel to second cleavage direction. Slat
Schistose unit as previous with irregular patches of kf-metasomatite and calcite. Strong partial to complete replacement of the potassium with sericite
Interbedded sheared limestone and very fine grained pelite. Weak chlorite alteration of the pelite. Weak hematite alteration of the dolomite.
Variably hematite altered sheared and foliated schist with fractures running sub-parallel to core axis infilled with calcite and pyrite. Weak boudinaged texture of small quartz grains.
Predominantly broken core through interval with increased mica growth giving vitreous lustre to broken faces. Mainly broken along general plane of foliation.
Banded magnetite>>sericite schist(?) with small quartz grains boudinaged parallel to the foliation of the rock. onset of magnetite coincident with the onset of pyrite mineralisation in foliations.
Foliated finely laminated and crackle-vined very fine grained black schist. Veins are infilled with weakly hm-altered calcite and have hm/kf(?) alteration of surrounding rock. Interbeds of diopside.

More micaceous interval with strong kf-porphyroblasts boudinaged parallel to foliation. Crosscutting veins of kf suggesting partial melt phase and ductile deformation. Gneissic texture with quartz/feldspar segregations. pervasive fine grained quartz.

Well foliated biotite chlorite schist with occasional bands of kf-metasomatism(?) parallel to foliation. 30cm interval of massive diopside altered carbonate from 257.8. Clayey broken core at downhole contact - possible small fault zone.

Massive strongly diopside altered quartz chlorite biotite skarn. 2-3mm patches of chlorite being cut/replaced by tiny microveins of diopside. faulted uphole contact. Gradational downhole contat with increasing quartz and kf content.

Well foliated qtz/bi schist with psammitic intervals. Frequent large intrusions of massive quratz and rare patchy diopside. Regular fracturing running parallel to foliations infilled with calcite/chlorite. Kf metasomatism in bands parallel to foliati

Well foliated quartz biotite schist strongly k-metasomatised with 70+% replacement of host rock. Frequent bands showing incomplete replacement moving parallel to foliation and partially replaced by kfs

Well foliated qtz/bi/kfs msc/mgn. Pervasive kf prophyroblasts aligned parallel to foliation - not boudinaged. Occasional cross-cutting veins of massive kfs >> qtz  with pyrite inclusions suggest partial melt. Increasing porphyroblast concentration DH

Increased porphyroblast content from previous with individual porphyroblasts in contact with one another parallel to rock's foliation. Coarse grained quartz crystals forming. Downhole content almost becoming granite with 10-30cm massive quartz veins.

Fine grained quartz biotite schist. Uphole contact in broken core but adjacent to massive quartz vein at end of migmatitic interval. Sparse kfs - very fine grained and patchy. Downhole contact with increasing kfs content and apperance of  porphyrobla
Light/medium pink kfs-rich porphyroblastic paragneiss with 3-5mm blasts of qtz/kfs. 3-4cm quartz macroveins and small patches of diopside-altered pelite.

Porphyroblastic biotite kfs qtz gneiss as previous with slightly reduced kfs content. Porphyroblasts aligned parallel to foliation of the rock. patchy sericitisation of potassic intervals - particularly around microveins cross cutting foliation.

Massive to weakly foliated quartz/kfs granite  with strong igenous interlocking texture of qtz/kfs. Foliations defined by lineament of quartz domains. Broken core - no orientation of foliations & Contacts lost.Likely a first melt intrusion.
Return to porphyroblastic domain - kfs qtz bi gneiss as prev. Becoming more strained and clayey downhole. Downhole contact in ~40cm of brittle fault zone.
Massive quartz vein likely exploiting fault zone with abundant biotite at uphole contact - quartz likely infilling void space. Small inclusions of kfs and sericite. Microveined with kfs.

Variably sheared porphyroblastic quartz/kfs/bi gneiss. Sheared intervals show strong sericite alteration of potassic domains and increased myrmitic/graphic texture of quartz/kfs .Predominantly broken core throughout - kfs-rich intervals appear more d
Massive quartz vein with kf-microveining and rare patchy carbonate with vuggy texture. Again possibly exploiting adjacent fault zone - considerably less inclusions than previous vein.

Medium-coarse grained kfs/quartz porphyroblastic gneiss with sheared texture and weak boudinaging of blasts. Occasional patches of sericite alteration on broken faces. 70+% broken core. Rare x-cutting kfs veins.
Highly fractured/boken gneiss as previous with intense sericite replacement of feldspar (perfect pseudomorphs of kfs, relict kfs nearly completely replaced)

Considerably less kfs than in previous intervals - biotite phyric sheared paragneiss with 3-7mm blasts. Sheared with weak boudinaged texture. Occasional patches of sericite alteraiton. Broken core at DH contact.
Massive quartz vein with kf microveins. Increasing kf content near downhole contact.
Foliated boudinaged quartz kfs biotite gneiss with variable ~70%-90% leucocratics. Frequent intervas of broken core.
Well foliated quartz biotite schist with sparse kfs porphyroblasts. Strongly K-metasomatism of selective beds parallel to foliation.
Well foliated quartz biotite schist with <1mm kf porphyroblasts. Foliations being crosscut by postassium microveins. 30cm quartz macrovein from 440.8
Massive quartz vein. Increasingly fractured and infilled with kf near downhole contact.

Quartz biotite schist with occasional zone of small porphyroblast growth. Multiple stages of alteration - potassic alteration of individual foliated horizons/patches followed by sericite replacement of potassium finally potassium veins cross cutting

Reduced foliation and disappearance of phorophyroblasts. Predominantly fine grained quartz biotite with weak chlorite alteration. Microscopic void space infilled with calcite. Highly broken core from 485.7m.

Medium grained quartz kfs biotite granitoid as preiously described. up and downhole contacts at steep angle to long core axis. No garnet in this interval. Likely intrusive. Macroveined with pegmatitic quartz/kfs.
Well foliatd and folded quartz biotit kfs paragneiss. Variable garnet content. Largest discernable folds ar ~35cm wavelength. Biotite zones begininng to have more chorite downhole.

Continuation of pevious unit. Speckles of deep brick clayey mineral adjacent to quartz/kf bands/patches. Not enough to change the chemistry but an unusual ateration mineral. Chlorite alteration is strongest in this interval and decreasing downhole.

Well milled fine grained clayey fault zone. subangular clasts of qtz/kfs supported by chlorite.

Massive medium grained quartz kfs>>bi granitoid. Sharp up and downhole contacts.

Massive medium grained quartz kfs>>bi granitoid. Sharp up and downhole contacts.

Biotite-rich gneiss with minor quartz foliations - no banding. Some quartz bands contain green quartz boudins. Distinct up and downhole contacts.

Medium grained amphibolite as previous with minor disseminated pyrrhotite. Minor zones of graphite alteration. Sharp downhole contact with limestone - appears conformable.

Massive to moderately foliated carbonate. Variably dolomitised . Speckled with chlorite altered subrounded 1-2mm clasts. Occasional thin zones of biotie in place of chlorite. minor patchy magnetite in place of chlorite. Possible clast of mam near UH
Massive diopside(?) altered interval pseudomorphing recrystallised carbonate. Strong chlorite alt of SDO at UH cnt. Strong Bi alteration at DH CNT
Recrystallised dolomitic limestone with specled ch +/- bi clasts as previous.
Massive diopside(?) altered interval pseudomorphing calcite as previous. Bands of intercalated massive bi and ch at up and downhole conacts.

Weakly foliated ch/bi clasts in recrystallised carbonate. THin inervals of ds-altered units as previous with contacts parallel to foliation. Interbeds of previous two units. Gradational DH contact with increasing ch/bi%

Increased ch and bi (+/-ph) % from previous interval. CLats of chlorite up to 1cm, Predominantly calcite (mg taken into ch rather than cb?). Inerbedded with similar recrystallied carb. with white mica instead of ch. Bedding plane at DH contact.
Bedded psammite. Fine grained rounded quartz sand with minor carbonate cement. Thin horizons of ch/carbonate as previous. Decrease in cb cement at DH contact
Fine grained rounded quartz psammite as previous with reduced cb cement. Crumbly and permeable. Bedded dh contact.
Massive chlorite speckled recrystallised limestone. Predominantly calcite as matrix. Thin intervals of cb-cemented psammite as previous.

Bedded fine grained rounded quartz psammite with increasing cb cement with depth. Pervasive minor phlogopite giving brown colouration. Beds of speckled ch in calcite matrix near downhole contact. Bedded dh contact.
Speckled to foliated chlorite in subrounded ~1-2mm clasts supported in recrystallised calcite matrix. Phlogopite disseminated throughout. Ch and Cb segregated and ppears bedded near base of interval.

Massive to very weakly foliated recrystallised calcite with fine grained phlogopite disseminated throughout. fine grained chlorite in subangular grains disseminated throughout. Bedded planar downhole contact. Increased foliated chlorite at downhole c

Foliated/bedded calcite with patchy/foliated chlorite alteration as previous. Minor phlogopite disseminations throughout. SOme chlorite with magnetite alteration near center of interval. Bedded DH contact.
Interbedded recrystallised carbonates with alternating dominance of ph and ch grains as previous. Predominantly ph-rich. bed thickness up to 1.5m
Significant increase in chlorite concentration. massive clasts of chlorite angular/square up to 1cm pseudomorphing cleavage planes - retrograde px? Calcite matrix as previous. EOH.
Fine grained olive brown siltstone with orange and red mottling. Trace quartz and becoing lighter downhole
Fine to medium grained subangular quartz. some pink quartz.
Fine to coarse grained quartz. Trace subangular feldspar clasts. Rare black lithics
Fine grained subangular quartz in silty cream-green matrix.
Medium grained subangular quartz with silty white matrix
Poorly sorted fine-coarse grained angular quartz
Poorly sorted fine to medim grained subrounded quartz with green silty matrix.
Fine grained sand and red silty matrix. Mica rich.
Chlorite-mica altered metasediments
Fine to medium grained quartz kfs-rich granitoid with mottled chlorite in regular 7mm patches. No visible micas. Variably weathered with ligh green clay alteration (smectite?)

Rubbly core - strongly faulted and altered variant of previous interval. Groundmass predominantly altered to chlorite or other clays. Angular clasts of granite still present. Short interval of dolomite sericite chlorite mica marble at 160-160.15m.

Highly weathered marble(?) groundmass is predominantly clay pseudomorphing granular calcite (?). Remaining carbonate is dolomitised. Variable chlorite concentration with increased chlorite occuring in conjunction with pale green (sericitised?) mica.
Massive grey/brow marble(?) less weathered than previous interval. Pervasive disseminated brown clay with occasional concetrated patches.

Highly weathered marble(?) groundmass is predominantly clay pseudomorphing granular calcite (?). Remaining carbonate is dolomitised. Variable chlorite concentration with increased chlorite occuring in conjunction with pale green (sericitised?) mica.

Continuation of previous unit with considerable increase in sericitised (?) mica concentration to above 80%. Carbonate is dolomitised. Rock is still weathered with granular clayey minerals in the groundmass pseudomorphing calcite(?)

Highly weathered marble(?) groundmass is predominantly clay pseudomorphing granular calcite (?). Remaining carbonate is dolomitised. Variable chlorite concentration with increased chlorite occuring in conjunction with pale green (sericitised?) mica.
Fault zone through previous interval. All of the above *may* be weathered granitoid but most likely carbonate.

Massive medium grained granular carbonate (dolomite) with disseminated chliorite in subrounded 1mm grains throughout. Variable biotite content typically less than 1% and occurring in small aggregates. Irregular soft vfg carbonate micro veins.
Continuation of previous unit with the exception of occasional white tremolite+/- carbonate microveins.
Massive highly clay altered dolomitic marble as previous with considerably reduced chlorite/sericite. Minor biotite throughout. Poorly cemented. Faulted downhole contact.

Massive fine grained dolomite with pervasive chlorite altertion throughout. Visually similar to greenstone. hardness of 2-3.  Rubbly faulted up and downhole contacts. Interval of lesser chlorite alteration similar to previous interval from 239.5-240.

Massive fine grained granular metamorphosed limestone with disseminated chlorite and biotite. Subrounded aggregates of biotite and/or chlorite up to .7cm - otherwise predominantly equigranular. Carbonate is calcite rather than DO as prev. Cb microvei
Gradational uphole contact evidenced by decreasing chlorite and biotite content. Grains are subrounded to subangular. Gradational downhole contact.
Continuation of previous unit with pervasive biotite>ch. Gradual downhole and uphole contacts.
Granular carbonate - continuation of previous unit with minor biotite and chlorite. Minor foliations dipping steeply to the NE
Incrased chlorite from previous interval - minor biotite. Gradual up and downhole contacts with increasing and decreasing ch. Carbonate is calcite.
Fine grained rounded quartz with minor dolomitic cement. Poorly cemented. Minor chlorite throughout. Flecs of biotite up to 1-2mm. Gradual downhole contact.

Equigranular calcite and chlorite. Chlorite habit is angular and infilling(?) between calcite grains. Equal percentages of calcite and chlorite. Sharp faulted downhle contact with slickenslides on contact plane.

Massive very fine grained recrystallised limestone with pervasive very finely disseminated chlorite throughout giving pale green/grey colour to the rock. Soft clear mineral also disseminated throughout - gypsum(?). Patches to bands of unfoliated DkGr

Massive recrystallised limestone as previous with variable chlorite content up to 60%. Sub-vertical foliations defined by compositional variation (decreased ch/cb and increased do/bi) striking NW/SE. Faulted downhole contact.
Fault zone through previous unit. Main modal mineralogy is recrystallised calcite + chlorite with minor biotite +/- minor sericite.

Massive recrystallised limestone as previous with variable chlorite content up to 60%. Sub-vertical foliations defined by compositional variation (decreased ch/cb and increased do/bi) striking NW/SE. Faulted downhole contact.
Broken to milled clayey core. Predominantly faulted through previous interval. Angular clasts of quartz at 402.6m possibly quartz vein exploiting fault plane(?).
Continuation of recrystallised limestone with granular chlorite sericite and phlogopite. Most abundant minerals are calcite and phlogopite.
Diffuse uphole contact with previous unit. Decreased phlogopite. Most abundant minerals are granular sericite and chlorite in calcite matrix. Diffuse downhole contact as well.

Massive mottled medium grained recrystallised limestone with speckled chlorite phlogopite and sericite. Calcite ammounts to ~50% of the rock. Foliations defined by chlorite-deficient bands. Bands are subvertical and striking NW/SE. Broken core at DH

Massive coarse grained quartz pegmatite with minor feldpsar. Feldspar opaque and variably white/green - possibly partial sericitisation. Irregularly shaped patches of ch up to .5cm. Broken core at UH and DH contacts - no visible slickenslides.

Massive mottled granular chlorite + sericite +/- phlogopite in recrystallised calcitic matrix. Subrounded blebs of massive biotite up to 1cm with edges are altering to chlorite. Diffuse downhole contact but generally subvertical striking NW-SE.

Texturally very similar to previous unit- compositionally CH/SE is absent. phlogopite up to 1mm disseminated evenly in calcite. CA matrix is metamorphosed to triple points - space inhibited. CH is rare and pseudomorphing a bladed mineral in aggregate

Massive biotite-rich interval - completely composed of biotite (phlogopite?) 90+% and calcite. Likely a compositional bed as the downhole contact is subvertical and strikes NW/SE as per previous bedding. 4cm massive ca vein at UH contact.

Metamorphosed carbonate with even 1mm phlogopite disseminations and rare patchy chlorite pseudomorphing bladed mineral as previous.Interval of pegmatite as prev desc. from 511.7-518.2. Contacts sub-vrtical striking NW/SE

Massive coarse to medium grained pegmatite/granitoid interval with speckled chlorite in blebs up to .5cm pseudomorphing biotite. Feldspar is white/green. Coarse grained at UH cnt becoming finer grained towards base. Contacts sub-vertical striking NW/

Metamorphosed carbonate with even 1mm phlogopite disseminations and rare patchy chlorite pseudomorphing bladed mineral as previous. Downhole contact dipping V.steeply SW striking NW/SE. Unoritented uphole contact but shallowly dipping.
Massiv mottled fine grained quartz with patchy chlorite and biotite. Uphole contact sub-vertical dipping steeply SW. Broken core at DH contact.

Massive coarse grained quartz/kfs pegmatite with variably white/green FS. Patchy chlorite possibly pseudomorphing phlogopite/biotite (more of a metagranitoid?). Rare minor patches of phlogopite. Faulted downhole contact - possibly sub-horizontal faul
Metamorphosed carbonate with even 1mm phlogopite disseminations and rare patchy chlorite pseudomorphing bladed mineral as previous. Downhole contact dipping moderately steeply to the NW.

Massive fine grained biotite phyric metased. Up and DH contacts dipping v.steeply to the nw. Mineralogy is predominantly biotite with patchy chlorite and minor calcite infill (<1mm) Compositional bedding pre metamorphism.

Metamorphosed carbonate with even 1mm phlogopite disseminations and rare patchy chlorite pseudomorphing bladed mineral as previous. Downhole contact diffuse/gradual with increasing CH - dipping steeply (almost vertical to the NE)

Texturally similar calcite and phlogopite as previous - large percentage of groundmass is chlorite +/- sericite rather than calcite. Calcite is less coarse grained/euhedral than in prev. intervals. No distinct contact - chlorite decreases.
Massive very fine grained sericite variably blue/green metased with medium grained tourmaline p.blasts and speckled brown phlogopite.

Metamorphosed carbonate with even 1mm phlogopite disseminations and rare patchy chlorite pseudomorphing bladed mineral as previous. Downhole contact diffuse/gradual with increasing CH. Very diffuse downhole contact

Massive fine to medium grained granular calcite chlorite biotte sericite metasediment. Mostly equigranular. Patches of fine grained red/purple altered mineral - altered Garnet? Downhole contact dipping steeply NE as prev.
Metamorphosed carbonate with even 1mm phlogopite disseminations and rare patchy chlorite pseudomorphing bladed mineral as previous.

Texturally similar to previous calcite rich marbles with slightly increased chlorite. Several 5-7cm fault zones with clear slickenslides and pervasive v.strong ch-alt of fault zones - minor calcite preserved in fault planes.
Metamorphosed carbonate with even 1mm phlogopite disseminations and rare patchy chlorite pseudomorphing bladed mineral as previous. Steeply NE-dipping downhole contact.
Massive coarse grained quartz feldspar pegmatite as previous with visible twins on feldspars and patchy <1.2cm garnet p.blasts. Patchy chlorite. Variably green feldspar - sericitised? EOH.

Fractured to broken interval with strong chlorite alteration on fracture planes. 2cm fracture sub-parallel to core axis infilled with ch and hm-alt dolomite. No visible slickenslides.

Interbedded siltstone and fine sandstone as previous with some intervals of apparent flaser bedding. If not a tectonic feature - sequence is younging upwards. Wavy bedding appears to be syn-sedimentary controlled. Rare frac infill /w var hm-alt dolom
Variably ch/hm-altered siltstone. Macroveins of yellow (siderite?) altered dolomote at top of interval - fracture controlled.  very broken to milled core at base of recorded interval.
Fractred and sheared siltstone with large pathes of quartz carbonate infilling voids. veining includes chlorite a yellow transparent mineral (siderite?) and hm-altered carbonate.
Interbedded variably hm>>ch-altered purple siltstone and grey sandstone. beds are wavy with no visible tectonic structure across axial planes - possibly syn-sedimentary or ripple bedding.
Fracture sub-parallel to core axis with ch/qtz/cb/py/cpy infill in interbedded silt+sand. Core is strained but not broken or sheared.
Interbedded variably hm>>ch-altered purple siltstone and grey sandstone. beds are wavy with no visible tectonic structure across axial planes - possibly syn-sedimentary or ripple bedding.
Increased percentage and thickness of sandier beds. Overall, unit is becoming sandier. Bedding appeas to be unfolded. Ripply beds - if flaser bedding- suggest younging upwards.

Faulted in up and downhole contacts- amygdaloidal aphanitic basaltic andesite with ch/qtz filled amygdales and qtz/cb veining. Hm-alteration typically surrounding veining and in some amygdales. Weakly disseminated magnetite.

Increased sandy beds interbedded with purple hm-altered siltstone. Patches of sand near base of interval. Rare do/qt veining. Wavy beds with bands of ch-alteration running along axial planes. Micro fractures with sericite alteraiton halos.

Decrease in thickness of sandy beds. Increase in amplitude of wavy beds - becoming strained to fractured. Large dolomite+qtz vpatches infilling fracture associated with ch/se alteration of siltstone. Bands of ch-alt along axial planes of wavy beds.

Intruded basaltic andesite - foliation of amygdales parallel to the contact. Increased amygdal size towards the middle of the interval. weak hm-alteration along fractures/veins.Contact cross-cuts bedding.
Interbedded silt and sandstone with increase in sandy intervals and wavy beds with ch-alteration along axial planes. Syn-sedimentary deformation.

Intruded basaltic andesite - foliation of amygdales parallel to the contact. Increased amygdal size towards the middle of the interval. weak hm-alteration along fractures/veins.Contact cross-cuts bedding.
Interbedded silts and sands with large patches of sand. Synsedimentary features in sandstone at 389.1m suggest younging upwards and wavy beds are due to syn-sed faulting.
Decreased sand content from previous interval. Wavy beds continue. weak chlorite alteration along axial planes.

Fractured and brecciated silttone with some intervals preserving bedding. Strong overprint of white mica with remenant hm-alteration in patches. Small interval of purple silt and sand as previously described

Interbedded silt and sandstone as previously described. wavy beds and weak sericite alteration surrounding rare carbonate veinin which cross cuts bedding. pink white mica/sericite alteration at downhole contact.
Three <30cm mafic intrusives as previously described surrounded by strongly sericite/white mica altered siltstone. Bedding is preserved. Alteration is strongest adjacent to intrusives.
Massive amygdaloidal basalt with weak foliation of amygdales. Intrusive - cross cutting bedding. Beds are sericite-altered surrounding the volcanic.
Interbedded silt and sand as previously described. Fractured and brecciated intervals infilled with dolomite/quartz +/- chlorite. Laminated + brecciated downhole contact.

Massive aphanitic intermediate intrusive with quartz-filled cavities (amy?) and weak pervasive hematite alteration being bleached out by white mica alteration (?) indistinct boundaries - possibly incoporating patches of sed into the intrusive.

Significantly less sandy interbeds than previous. Increased white mica/sericite alteration with patches of strong sericite overprinting. Beds are commonly disrupted to broken and sericite is strongest adjacent to the fractures. occasional sdo/qtz vei
5cm clayey chloritic faults at uphole contact and 468.7m. Otherwise, broken core with fractures foliated along similar planes. Fault is through sericite-altered siltstone with rare sandy beds.
Interbedded purple hm-altered siltstone and grey fine sand. Sericite alteration haloing small fractures in rock.

Bedded purple hm-altered siltstone with occasional grey sandy beds. Intruded with patches of black basaltic volcanic. Strong sericite alteration along bedding planes around intrusives. Bedding diopping Steep S. Brecciated adjacent to intruded volcani
Reduced sandy layers in predominantly purple hematite-altered siltstone. Some larger patches of sand at 495m.
Sheard siltstone with rare patches of chlorite and sericite. Not broken core but beds predominantly disrupted and fragments of beds are subrounded.

Interbedded silt and sand with increased sand from previous interval. Large patches of sand at 552m. Small fault zones at 520.3-520.5 and 550-551.6m with broken core and sericite alteration about fractures. Wavy beds with weak ch-alt along axial plan
Uphole contact dipping steeply to the north east. DH contact dipping steeply west (?) and strongly sericitised with chilled margin. Magnetite disseminated near top of interval - decreases downhole.
Weakly fractured beds of silt and sand with sericite alteration around sandier beds and martite veining along martite beds. Pyrite injected along sandier beds.

Increased sandy beds from previous interval. Syn-sedimentary faults as previous with chlorite-alt along axial planes. Sericite alteration where microveined. Near downhole contact increase in hematite alteration to dark red/brown colour.

Amygdaloidal intermediate/mafic intrusive with amygdal size increasing towards middle of interval. Magnetite disseminated throughout but strongest at edges. Uphole contact dipping steeply NW. DH cnt dipping steeply W.

Bedded to massive siltstone with some fractures and carbonate-filled crackle veins. Reduced sericite alteration from previous interval. gradual reduction of sericite towards downhole contact.
Significant increase in coherency and frequency of sany beds from previous interval. fairly regular planar beds with some intervals of syn-sedimentary faulting.
Predominantly broken core through previous interval. No visible slickenslides. May just be broken core.
Interbedded silt and sand as previously described with possible fold hinge about 662m with concentric circles of sand/silt  rather than bands.
